Synchronization:
When multiple threads access shared data → Race Condition so we need Synchronization 
class Counter {
    int count = 0;
    synchronized void increment() {
        count++;
    }
}


Types of Synchronization:
  1. Method Level - synchronized void display() {}
  2. Block Level (Better ✅)
          void display() {
            synchronized(this) {
                // critical section
            }
        }
  3. Static Synchronization - Lock on class object : static synchronized void show() {} 
    Static synchronization means using synchronized on a static method, 
    so the lock is applied at the class level (not object level).
    Lock is on: ClassName.class not on this ❌
    Used when:
        Data is shared across all objects
        You want only one thread across entire class to access it

Static vs Instance Synchronization 
    Feature	          Instance Sync	        Static Sync
    Lock	            Object (this)        	Class (.class)
    Scope	            Per object	          Entire class
    Threads allowed  	One per object	      One per class
Will two threads run simultaneously? No if static , yes for Instance Synchronization
Mixing static & instance sync - Can run simultaneously → may cause issues
Can static and instance synchronized methods run together? YES (different locks)

synchronized vs volatile
Synchronized:
  Provides mutual exclusion (lock)
  Only one thread at a time can access
  Ensures atomicity + visibility
Volatile:
  no atomicity only visibility
  no lock
  faster
  Guarantees:Changes made by one thread are visible to others immediately
  Why is count++ not thread-safe even with volatile?  
    Because it is not atomic. Read, write and increement. 
    fix using synchronization or AtomicInteger.incrementAndGet()


Problem with synchronized:
    No timeout
    No try mechanism
    No fairness control
    Automatically managed (less control)
Lock solves:
    Try acquiring lock without blocking
    Timeout support
    Interruptible lock
    Better control
Lock:
  A Lock is a more flexible alternative to synchronized used to control access to shared resources.
  Comes from: java.util.concurrent.locks
  import java.util.concurrent.locks.*;
  Lock lock = new ReentrantLock();
  lock.lock(); // acquire
  try {
      System.out.println("Critical section");
  } finally {
      lock.unlock(); // must release
  }

ReentrantLock:
  A ReentrantLock allows the same thread to acquire the lock multiple times.
  Based on:AbstractQueuedSynchronizer (AQS)
  Maintains: State (lock count) and Queue (waiting threads)
  Re = again , Same thread can re-enter lock
    ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();
    lock.lock();
    lock.lock(); // allowed
    try {
        System.out.println("Inside");
    } finally {
        lock.unlock();
        lock.unlock(); // must match lock count
    }
    
    tryLock() (Non-blocking) - Avoids waiting → useful for deadlock prevention 
                              lock.tryLock()
    tryLock with Timeout - Prevents infinite waiting 
                            lock.tryLock(2, TimeUnit.SECONDS)
    Fair Lock - Threads get lock in FIFO order, Slightly slower 
                      ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock(true);
    Interruptible Lock -Thread can be interrupted while waiting
          lock.lockInterruptibly();

❌ Forgetting unlock - Causes deadlock
❌ Unlock without lock - lock.unlock(); // IllegalMonitorStateException
❌ Not using finally -Lock may never release
Can multiple threads enter lock? - ❌ No (only one at a time)

Deadlock:
  A deadlock occurs when two or more threads are waiting forever for each other’s locks.
Thread 1 → locks A → waits for B
Thread 2 → locks B → waits for A
How to Detect Deadlock: Using JDK Tool
program:
    ThreadMXBean bean = ManagementFactory.getThreadMXBean();
    long[] ids = bean.findDeadlockedThreads();
How to Fix Deadlock:
  Lock Ordering (BEST PRACTICE)
  Use Timeout Lock
  Reduce Nested Locks

Deadlock → threads are waiting (blocked) , CPU usage is low, due to waiting
Livelock → threads are running but not progressing, cpu usage is high, its due to over coordination

livelock:
  A livelock occurs when threads are not blocked, but they keep changing their state in response to each other and never make progress.
  Threads are active (running) but still stuck logically
    Thread 1 → "You go first"
    Thread 2 → "No, you go first"
    Thread 1 → "Okay you go"
    Thread 2 → "No you go"

Why Livelock Happens?
    Threads trying to be too polite
    Continuous retries
    Overuse of tryLock() without control
    Excessive coordination logic
How to Fix Livelock:
  Add Random Delay (Backoff Strategy)
  Reduce Coordination
  Limit Retries
  Use Proper Locking Strategy

Daemon thread:
  runs background thread that supports other thread.
  low priority background threads
  when non-daemon thread (all user thread) terminates then it will terminate daemon thread
  mostly used for Monitoring , logs , Garbage collections, Background timers and Cleanup tasks
  not suitable for transaction ,DB connections
  thread.setDaemon(true); before thread.start() otherwise throws IllegalThreadStateException.
  isDaemon() used to check whether thread is daemon or not.

User Vs Daemon:
  User thread is for main task Daemon is for background task
  JVM wait for User thread not for daemon
  Lifecycle is independent for User , ends with JVM for daemon
  example : Main - User , GC - Daemon

